%U A394854 1,2,5,1,3,1,2,8,1,4,1,2,3,1,1,2,1,3,6
%N A394854 Sequence where k is appended after every F(k+1) occurrences of 1 where F(k) is k-th term of the Fibonacci sequence (A000045), with multiple values following a 1 listed in order.
%C A394854 The density of k in this sequence is 1/((C-1)*F(k+1)), where C is the reciprocal Fibonacci constant (A079586). This can be viewed as a probability mass function since it is normalized to sum to 1.
%C A394854 The arithmetic mean approaches Sum_{k>0} k/((C-1)*F(k+1)) = 2.52578594152480... in the limit.
%C A394854 The geometric mean approaches Product_{k>1} k^(1/((C-1)*F(k+1))) = 1.965405525298... in the limit.
%C A394854 The sequence is generated by the D'Hondt (or Jefferson) apportionment method applied to the given distribution. - _Pontus von Brömssen_, Apr 11 2026
%H A394854 Jwalin Bhatt, <a href="/A394854/b394854.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A394854 Wikipedia, <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D%27Hondt_method">D'Hondt method</a>.
%e A394854 After every 2 ones we see a 2,
%e A394854 after every 3 ones we see a 3,
%e A394854 after every 5 ones we see a 4 and so on.
%o A394854 (Python)
%o A394854 from itertools import islice
%o A394854 from functools import lru_cache
%o A394854 @lru_cache
%o A394854 def fibonacci(k):
%o A394854     return fibonacci(k-1) + fibonacci(k-2) if k > 1 else k
%o A394854 def sample_fibonacci_distribution():
%o A394854     n, num_reached = 0, 1
%o A394854     while n := n+1:
%o A394854         yield 1
%o A394854         for num in range(2, num_reached+2):
%o A394854             if n % fibonacci(num+1) == 0:
%o A394854                 yield num
%o A394854                 num_reached += num == num_reached+1
%o A394854 A394854 = list(islice(sample_fibonacci_distribution(), 120))
%Y A394854 Cf. A000045, A079586, A393595, A394540, A395000.
%K A394854 nonn,new
%O A394854 1,3
